wn, while others are not. But all are creators of private and grand designs—makers of the worlds they inhabited.The Forest unfolds in brief stories. Each episode reveals an intricate lost world. Characters cross paths or go their own ways, each striving for something different but together forming a pattern of life. For Alexander Nemerov, the forest is a description of American society, the dense and discontinuous woods of nation, the foliating thoughts of different people, each with their separate shade and sun. Through vivid descriptions of the people, sights, smells, and sounds of Jacksonian America, illustrated with paintings, prints, and photographs, The Forest brings American history to life on a human scale.Published in association with the Center for Advanced Study in the Visual Arts, National Gallery of Art, Washington, DC  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aArt and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAlexander Jackson Davis.  aAlexander Nemerov.  aAntiquarian.  aArsenic.  aAshbel Smith.  aBenjamin Henry Latrobe.  aBook.  aBurial.  aCahokia.  aCaroline Lee Hentz.  aChestnut.  aChurch bell.  aClaude Lorrain.  aCotton Tree (Sierra Leone).  aD. H. Lawrence.  aDaguerreotype.  aDelicacy.  aDickcissel.  aEasel.  aEdgar Allan Poe.  aEngraving.  aFacsimile.  aFanny Kemble.  aFine art.  aFireplace.  aForest floor.  aFrancis Parkman.  aGermination.  aGreat Dismal Swamp.  aHandkerchief.  aHarriet Tubman.  aHelen Jewett.  aHiram Powers.  aHudson River.  aHyde Hall.  aIllustration.  aIndian removal.  aJacques Maritain.  aJames Fenimore Cooper.  aJane McCrea.  aJean-Jacques Rousseau.  aJohn Constable.  aJohn James Audubon.  aJohn Quidor.  aJohn Vanderlyn.  aJoslyn Art Museum.  aKar